Key Match Events: The Arizona Diamondbacks came back from a 2-1 deficit in the fourth inning and won the game 4-2.
Brandon Pfaadt struck out two batters to escape a jam in the fourth inning.
Joe Mantiply, Ryan Thompson, Andrew Saalfrank, Kevin Ginkel, and Paul Sewald combined to throw five shutout innings.
Pre-Game Insights: The Diamondbacks were considered underdogs throughout the postseason and had a negative run differential over 162 games.
The Phillies had a $246 million payroll, more than twice that of the Diamondbacks.
The Diamondbacks were expected to lose to the Phillies, with ticket prices on the secondary market dropping dramatically.
Post-Match Reflections: Manager Torey Lovullo said that he kept receipts of those who doubted his team and was proud to see them eat their words.
General manager Mike Hazen said that the team's success was a result of their ability to overcome adversity and that they wanted to play in front of tough crowds like the Phillies.
The team celebrated their victory with a chaotic and joyful scene in the clubhouse, with players and staff dousing each other with beer and cigars.
Miscellaneous Highlights: The Diamondbacks are going to the World Series, a thought that seemed beyond comprehension just two years ago.
The team has been counted out at various points throughout the season, including when they lost 110 games in 2021.
The Phillies were the story of the playoffs until the Diamondbacks came in and changed the narrative.
Others: The Diamondbacks' victory was seen as a validation of their team's resilience and ability to overcome adversity.
The team's success was also seen as a testament to the leadership of manager Torey Lovullo and general manager Mike Hazen.
The Diamondbacks will now face the Texas Rangers in the World Series.
